		{"id":"9ff302debac188fd","type":"text","text":"# Explain the backend in natural language\n\nUse this like you’re talking to the class — not reading jargon off the slide.\n\n---\n\n## 30-second version\n\n> When you use my app, the **website you see** is only half the story. The **backend** is what runs on the server when you click Save, connect a bank, or ask AI a question.\n>\n> **Next.js API routes** receive those requests. **Prisma** is the translator between my code and the database. **Postgres** is where everything is stored — ledger, documents, Plaid links.\n>\n> For development I use **Postgres in Docker** on my laptop. In production the same data lives on **Neon** in the cloud, and the app runs on **Vercel**. I use **DBeaver** to open the database and check tables like `financial_states` — that’s for me as the developer, not for end users.\n\n---\n\n## Walk through the slide (point at each box)\n\n**1 — Next.js API**  \n> “This is the **server door**. When the browser or Telegram sends ‘save this expense’ or ‘answer this question’, the request hits an **API route** — code under `/api` that runs on Vercel, not in the user’s browser.”\n\n**2 — Prisma ORM**  \n> “I don’t write raw SQL for every query. **Prisma** lets me say things like ‘get all financial events’ in TypeScript, and it turns that into safe database calls. It also keeps the schema typed so I make fewer mistakes.”\n\n**3 — Postgres database**  \n> “**Postgres** is the **single source of truth** — income, bills, uploaded document metadata, Plaid balance history, and RAG embeddings. Forecast and chat all read from here.”\n\n**4 — Neon (cloud)**  \n> “In production, Postgres runs on **Neon** — managed database in the cloud. Vercel connects with a secret connection string the user never sees.”\n\n**5 — Docker Postgres (local)**  \n> “On my laptop I run the **same kind of database in Docker** so I can develop without touching production data.”\n\n**6 — Vercel / DBeaver**  \n> “**Vercel** hosts the Next.js app and API. **DBeaver** is my tool to inspect the database — run queries, see the ER diagram. Users never open DBeaver; it’s for debugging and demos.”\n\n**7 — Diagram (if you show it)**  \n> “Here’s the **financial_states** table in DBeaver — you can see how ledger and forecast tie back to real rows in the database, not something the AI made up.”\n\n---\n\n## Simple analogy (works well in Q&A)\n\n> “The **API** is the waiter. **Prisma** is the kitchen staff who know how to read the recipe book. **Postgres** is the pantry where everything is stored. **Vercel** is the restaurant building. **Neon** is the pantry in the cloud; **Docker** is the pantry on my desk for testing.”\n\n---\n\n## Tie to your project’s main idea\n\n> “The backend matters because **money must be computed and stored on the server**. The AI doesn’t remember your balances — it asks the API, which reads **Postgres** through **Prisma**. That’s how we keep answers trustworthy.”\n\n---\n\n## If someone asks: “Why not put the database in the browser?”\n\n> “Because anyone could steal the password and change your ledger. Secrets stay on **Vercel**; the browser only gets **answers**, not keys.”\n\n---\n\n## One slide subtitle (optional)\n\n> **Backend:** API on Vercel → Prisma → Postgres (Neon in prod, Docker locally)\n\nGood luck — speak slowly on Prisma vs Postgres; that’s where people often get confused. **Prisma = code layer**, **Postgres = where data lives**.","x":-560,"y":-720,"width":1120,"height":840}
	],
	"edges":[]
}